This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it focuses on building efficient convolutional neural networks for image classification and object detection tasks. It also involves the use of structured sparse and low-rank kernels, which are commonly used in computer vision research. Additionally, the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories as it involves the design and optimization of deep neural networks. The use of complementary conditions and the comparison with state-of-the-art models also suggest that the paper may belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category as convolutional neural networks are commonly used in text classification and sentiment analysis tasks.
